description: From Middle English dunchen, of uncertain origin. Possibly from the noun (see below); or of North Germanic origin, related to Old Swedish diunga (“to hit, knock”), dialectal Swedish dunka (“to beat”); or from Middle English dengen, from Old English denġan, denċġan (“to knock, ding”), from Proto-Germanic *dangijaną (“to bang, knock”). Compare English dinge.

verbs.description: dunch (third-person singular simple present dunches, present participle dunching or dunchin, simple past and past participle dunched)

entries.meaning: (Tyneside) To knock against; to hit, punch
(Tyneside) To crash into; to bump into.
(Scotland) To gore with the horns, as a bull.
(Britain) To jog, especially with the elbow.

description: From Middle English dunche, perhaps from Old English *dynċ, from Proto-Germanic *dunkiz.
Compare Old Norse dykr, dynkr (“a crashing noise”), Danish dunk (“a blow”), Swedish dunk (“a thump, clap”), Norwegian dunk (“a knock, bump”).

entries.meaning: (golf) A fat hit from a claggy lie.

description: Blend of dinner +‎ lunch, probably in imitation of brunch.

entries.meaning: (informal, rare) A leisurely meal between lunch and dinner in the late afternoon or early evening (about 3-5 p.m.), usually instead of lunch or dinner.
examples: I have a lunchtime meeting tomorrow, so let's have dunch together instead.
